President Joseph R. Biden Jr. of the United States and President Yoon Suk Yeol of the Republic of Korea met in Washington to commemorate the 70th anniversary of the U.S.-ROK Alliance. They reaffirmed their commitment to deepening security cooperation and developing stronger mutual defense and deterrence. The Alliance aims to achieve a secure and brighter future for both nations by increasing global cooperation, regional engagement, and bilateral ties. They also condemned Russia's war of aggression against Ukraine and expressed support for Ukraine's sovereignty and territorial integrity. The two Presidents emphasized the importance of diplomacy with North Korea and called on the DPRK to return to negotiations. They also discussed climate change, economic cooperation, and strengthening the Indo-Pacific region. The U.S.-ROK Alliance extends to cyberspace and space, and they pledged to enhance cybersecurity cooperation and explore cooperation in space exploration. They also committed to deepening people-to-people ties and educational cooperation. Overall, the article highlights the commitment of the U.S. and ROK to a strong and prosperous future for their alliance.